{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You get only one chance to receive an augment on any given contest. Failure does not allow other augment attempts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Augments can, however, combine with other modifiers, including those from benefits of victory and from plot augments.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is impossible to augment an augment roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Augments last for the duration of a single contest, whether simple or extended.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.4.1 Quick Augments\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Although some players like the uncertainty of rolling Game Masters may choose to run their game with calculated augments: divide the augmenting ability by 5 and round up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.4.2 Plot Augments\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A plot augment is earned by overcoming a particular plot obstacle created by the Game Master. The magnitude of the plot augment is +3, +6, +9, or +M. The more challenging the plot obstacle, the higher the augment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.5 Armor and Weapons, Possessions and Equipment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Questworlds models arms and armor like it does everything else: any piece of gear, if sufficiently important to even mention, is treated as an ability the PC uses to solve problems.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The degree to which a PC can overcome an obstacle with their armor and weapons depends not on any qualities inherent to the objects themselves, but to the points the player has allocated to the ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The difference between types of armor or weapons lies in the types of actions the player can describe, and what the PC can accomplish in unrelated actions and unusual contests.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, Questworlds treats your possessions and equipment like it does everything else: as abilities you can use to solve problems, or to augment other abilities, which you then use to solve problems.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Having inappropriate equipment can result in an action being treated as a Stretch.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.6 Wealth\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In most settings, wealth is treated as just another ability you use to overcome obstacles. Your ability is not an objective measure of the size of your fortune, but instead indicates how well you solve problems with money and resources.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 3. Character Creation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.1 As-You-Go Method\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Concept The concept is a brief phrase, often just a couple of words, that tells the GM and other players what the PC does and how they act. When in doubt, start with a noun or phrase indicating the PC\u8217's profession or area of expertise, and modify it with an adjective suggesting a dominant personality trait:\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab haughty priestess\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab hotshot lawyer\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab nai\u776?ve warrior\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab noble samurai\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab remorseful assassin\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab sardonic ex-mercenary\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab slothful vampire\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Now provide the character with a name.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab If the series uses other keywords, such as those for culture or religion, the PC may have them for free.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab When events in the story put the PC in a situation where the player wants them to do something, the player makes up an applicable ability on the spot. The first time the PC uses an ability (including the two the PC starts play with), assign an ability rating to it. This may be a breakout ability from a keyword. The PC is restricted to only one Sidekick.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab If the player wants, describe flaws.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Once the PC has 12 abilities (including the two for character concept), and up to three flaws the player is done creating their character.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.2 Assigning Ability Ratings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A player has now defined a PC\u8217's abilities. These tell everyone what the PC can do. Now the player assigns numbers to each ability, called ratings, which determine how well they do these things.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The player assigns a starting rating of 17 to the ability they find most important or defining. Although most players consider it wisest to assign this rating to their area of expertise, which is also often a keyword, they don\u8217't have to do this. All other abilities start at a rating of 13.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Now the player may spend up to 20 points to boost any of the PC\u8217's various ability ratings, including keywords. Each point spent increases a rating by 1 point. The player can\u8217't spend more than 10 points on any one ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some genre packs may require PCs to have additional keywords that reflect the setting. These additional keywords come from the 12 ability allowance, so in many genres the PCs will have fewer wildcard abilities but better fit the setting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.3 Keywords\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A player may build a character around one or more keywords. A keyword gives the PC a package deal: the PC gets a number of abilities by selecting a pre-existing character concept, which the player then modifies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Keywords are best suited for use as the character\u8217's core area of expertise.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In certain genres, characters may require multiple keywords: for example, one for area of expertise, another for species or culture, and perhaps a third for religious af liation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Here are two ways to handle keywords. If in doubt, choose Umbrella.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keywords as Packages}: Treat keywords simply as shorthand for a package of abilities. These can be boosted together during character creation, but are too unrelated to increase together during a game. Players are still free to use the keyword as an ability, and in fact may prefer to write only the specific abilities they\u8217've improved on their character sheet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keywords as an Umbrella}: Treat keywords both as raisable abilities and as a collection of more specific abilities. This approach keeps the character sheet from getting too cluttered but encourages specialization. Players write specialized abilities under the keyword, along with how much they\u8217've improved them:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In some settings, an ability may be listed in more than one of a character\u8217's keywords. Choose only one to detail it under.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.3 Flaws\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A player may assign up to three flaws to their PC. Common flaws include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Personality traits:surly, petty, compulsive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Physical challenges:blindness, lameness, diabetes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Social hurdles: outcast, ill-mannered, hated by United supporters.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Flaws are assigned a rating equivalent to the PC\u8217's abilities. The first flaw is rated at the highest ability, the second shares the same rating as the second-highest ability, and the third equals the lowest ability. Certain keywords include flaws. Flaws gained through keywords do not count against the limit of three chosen flaws. All flaws after the third are given the same rating as the third ability. A player may designate flaws from keywords as their first or second-ranked flaw. When flaws manifest during play, the GM places the PC in a contest against them, rolls their associated ability ratings as Resistances to the PC\u8217's efforts. This method applies to flaws that primarily present the character with additional obstacles to overcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 GMs may decide during play that certain aws are better expressed as penalties to the PC\u8217's attempts to overcome other resistances. Divide the value by 5 and round (a flaw of 19 imposes a \u8211-4 penalty). This is appropriate where the player specifies that your ability to solve problems drops under certain specific conditions. Examples might include: * Tongue-tied in large gatherings. * Lousy with a stick shift. * Can\u8217't stand snakes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 4. Optional Mechanics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.1 Resolution Methods\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An optional resolution method is also available as follows:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.1.1.1 Extended Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Most conflicts should be resolved using the simple contest rules. However, every so often, you\u8217'll want to stretch out a resolution, breaking it down into a series of smaller actions, increasing the suspense the players feel as they wait to see if they succeed or fail.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sequence of die rolls, between one or more PCs and one or more supporting characters, breaks the conflict resolution into a series of actions. This method trades speed for detail.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All contest types can resolve the actions of multiple characters acting at once, on either side of the conflict.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.2 Resistance Progression\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After two sessions of play, the base resistance increases by 1. After every subsequent two-session interval, it increases by another point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 GMs may prefer other progression schemes that reflect the rate of advancement in their game, such as every four sessions of play (used in Heroquest 2.1e), or even every campaign.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.3 Degrees of Success\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Often all you need to know to interpret the results of a resolution is whether the character succeeded or failed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes, you\u8217'll want to know how well a PC succeeded, or how badly he failed. This may be important in providing consequences or benefits, that drive futher story.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All of the resolution methods have an option to yield the degrees of success for the victor. The possible degrees of success, from least to greatest, are: marginal, minor, major, complete. Ties are also possible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a PC contests against NPCs or abstract forces, the interpretation of the results reveals whether the PC gains the prize, and any consequences or benefits for the PC, and the GM narrate the fate of the NPCS or other forces depending on what makes sense. However, when two PC are engaged in a contest then a success for one contestant means a corresponding failure for the loser.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 So whilst in a PC vs.\u160?PC duel the PC would only be killed on a Complete Defeat, an NPC, described as a resistance, might be killed on any victory, depending on how the prize was framed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Tie}: Tie means no result. Effort was expended, but the net result is that nothing consequential occurs, or else both sides lose or gain equally. If this is confusing, the PC gains a Marginal Victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Marginal Victory}: Yes, but\u8230?\u160?The PC gets what they want, but there are complications, the effect is more limited than they desired, or they have to make a hard choice between benefits or\u160?accept a loss to get one\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Minor Victory}: Yes\u8230? The PC gets exactly what they want i.e.\u160?the stakes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Major & Complete Victory}: Yes, and\u8230? The PC get the stakes, and something else. The PC gains something, stealing a\u160?possession, gaining a new follower, or become renowned in song. If you want to distinguish a Complete the effect is often permanent and no new contests should be framed for this prize.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Marginal Defeat}: No, but\u8230?\u160?The PC doesn\u8217't get what they want, they lose, but it\u8217's not a total loss. They are able to salvage something from the defeat, a little\u160?more if they sacrifice something other than the prize to their opponent,\u160?that the opponents agrees to take instead.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Minor Defeat}: No\u8230? They don\u8217't get what they want, they lose the stakes. Any consequences or complications such as injury or loss of influence are short term and easily shrugged off. Just take the\u160?loss and rest up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Major & Complete Defeat}: No and\u8230?\u160?You don\u8217't get what you want, and\u160?there are long-term consequences. The situation might grow worse or more complicated or you might suffer adverse consequences\u160?that will require other conflicts to resolve: an injury that\u160?needs a healer, an insult that\u160?requires a formal apology, a loss of influence with the community that requires a triumph to win their trust again etc. You might be dead, or as good as. Or perhaps you lose something, an item is taken from you, a follower deserts you, your reputation lies in ruins as poets mock your defeat. If you want to distinguish, a Complete should be bigger loss than a Major, but you can ignore this distinction often.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use the degree of success to determine any side effects or lingering consequences, but be sure to describe the success in narrative terms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the is using a Stretch, then major or complete victories they might score are instead treated as minor victories.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.4 Consequences\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Contests, in addition to deciding whether the character gets the prize he was after, carry additional side effects, or consequences. These are negative if the character loses, and positive if he wins.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The GM may simply determine these from what makes fictional sense, given the agreed prize for the contest, as described above. Optionally the GM may impose Consequences of Defeat or provide Benefits of Victory if they desire ongoing penalties or bonuses. This rule is used in conjuction with Degrees of Success. The GM should always respond to the flow of the story, if narrative consequences are enough, don\u8217't reach for additional mechanical penalties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.4.1 The Consequences of Defeat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When heroes lose contests, they may suffer consequences: literal or metaphorical injuries which make it harder for the heroes to use related abilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8226? In a fight or test of physical mettle, heroes wind up literally wounded. \u8226? In a social contest, they may suffer damage to their reputations. \u8226? If commanding a war, they lose battalions, equipment, or territories. \u8226? In an economic struggle, they lose money, other resources, or opportunities. \u8226? In a morale crisis, heroes may suffer bouts of crippling self-doubt.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 From the least to the most punishing, the five levels of consequences are: Hurt, Impaired, Injured, Dying, and Dead. The first four are possible results of any contest. Dying heroes become dead, unless they receive intervention of some sort.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.4.1.1 Healthy\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PCs who aren\u8217't in a state of adversity at all are considered healthy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is possible to seem banged up without suffering any measurable penalties. If you get into an extended contest during which you were at a disadvantage for a long time and nally came from behind for the win, you may seem bruised, winded, anxious, or otherwise the worse for wear. Although this apparent harm may yield you useful sympathy, it doesn\u8217't actually slow you down at all.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.4.1.2 Dazed\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In some situations, the Narrator may rule that a character is dazed. They are conscious but unable to initiate actions of their own. If another character engages them in a contest, they can snap out of it and defend themselves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.4.1.3 Hurt\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A hurt PC shows signs of adversity and finds it harder to succeed at contests related to their defeat. Either their flesh or pride may be bruised. Until the PC recovers, they suffer a \u8211-3 penalty to all related abilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Characters may suffer multiple hurts to the same ability. These are cumulative until recovery occurs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unless the GM has a compelling dramatic reason to decide otherwise, hurts vanish at the end of a session, after one day of rest per accumulated hurt, or when in-game events justify their removal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.4.1.4 Impaired\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An Impaired PC has taken a jarring blow, physically, socially, or emotionally, and is much likelier to fail when attempting similar actions in the future. THey suffers a \u8211-6 penalty to all related abilities. Impairments combine with hurts and with other impairments.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As bad as the character\u8217's condition may be, there\u8217's nothing wrong with him that some prolonged inactivity won\u8217't fix. A single impairment goes away after one week of rest, or when an in-game event (like miraculous or extraordinary treatment) occurs to make their removal seem believable.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.4.1.5 Injured\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An injured PC has suffered a debilitating shock to the system, one which renders them all but helpless.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To even participate in a contest, they must succeed at a prior contest of wherewithal to rouse themself to action. Appropriate abilities for contests of wherewithal might include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8226? Physical action: Endurance, High Pain Threshold, Grim Determination, etc. \u8226? Intellectual activity: Concentration, Iron Will, Love Of Country (if action to be attempted is patriotic), etc. \u8226? Social humiliation: Savoir Faire, Un appable, Stoic Dignity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A contest of wherewithal faces a Moderate resistance. Even if the injured PC succeeds at the contest of wherewithal, they take an automatic bump down whenever they use any related ability in a contest. (The bump down does not apply to the contest of wherewithal itself.) Where it seems apt, the GM may choose to ignore the bump down if the PC scores a major or complete victory on the contest of wherewithal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any active hurts or impairments continue to be counted against him as well.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.4.1.6 Dying\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A dying PC will, without rapid and appropriate intervention, soon expire. To save them, the PCs must typically overcome a story obstacle and/or succeed at a difficult contest. According to the conventions of dramatic storytelling, the character typically has just enough time left for the other characters to make this one attempt.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Successful intervention leaves the PC injured. Depending on the narrative circumstances, a complete victory on the intervention attempt may leave them merely impaired.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If intervention fails, the character will die, but not necessarily immediately. Although irrevocably doomed, they may survive long enough to deliver a poignant final speech.The PC is unable to perform any task complicated enough to require a contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Like other states of adversity, dying may be literal or metaphorical. Your standing in society, business or politics may be on the brink of permanent extinction. You may be facing mental death\u8212-a permanent lapse into madness or senility.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.4.1.7 Dead\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A PC who dies as a result of physical injuries is gone from the game, period.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Death from a non-physical contest will likely be metaphorical. If you die in an economic, social, spiritual, or artistic contest, you permanently lose abilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Even only metaphorically dead, the GM may declare that the PC has undergone changes so dire as to make them unplayable. They may be incurably insane, or so socially shamed that they retire to a life of obscurity or religious meditation. They may be shunned by all around them, sent into permanent exile, or sentenced to long-term imprisonment with no hope of escape.\par}
