{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.4.3 Recovery and Healing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Consequences of Injured or less lapse on their own with the passage of time. However, you\u8217'll often want to remove them ahead of schedule, with the use of abilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.4.3.1 Healing Abilities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The ability used to bring about recovery from a state of adversity must relate to the type of harm sustained by the victim.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Physical injuries can be healed by medical abilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Mental traumas, including those of con dence and morale, may be removed with mundane psychology or through extraordinary abilities. They might also be removed through a dramatic confrontation between the victim and the source of the psychic injury.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Social injuries must be healed through social abilities. They probably require public expiation of some sort, often including a negotiation with the offended parties and the payment of reparations, either tangible or symbolic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Damage to items and equipment requires some sort of repair ability. Extraordinary items may require genre-specific expertise: a broken magic ring may require a ritual to reforge.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Healing attempts will almost always unfold as simple contests. An exception might be a medical drama, in which surgeries would comprise the suspenseful set-piece sequences of the game.\par}
