{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 4.4.3.3 Consequences of Healing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A successful healing attempt removes one level of adversity for each level of victory. A major defeat increases the subject\u8217's consequence of defeat by 1; a complete defeat adds an additional 2 levels to the consequence of adversity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.5 Optional: Modifiers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Where an ability rating represents a general ability to succeed in the narrative, modifiers reflect specific conditions that may make it easier or harder to overcome particular obstacles. They are applied to your ability to get a final target number (TN).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Positive modifiers are called bonuses; negative modifiers are called penalties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Positive modifiers, or bonuses, may raise an ability high enough to gain a mastery, in which case the character gets the bumps up or down that a mastery would normally supply.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Negative modifiers, or penalties, may lower an ability to the point where it loses one or more masteries. In this case, the character loses the bumps up or down he would normally get.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Modifiers should only be used to alter a PC\u8217's target number to respect unusual circumstances he helped to create, or has some control over. If an unusual situation applies to a resistance, change the resistance number.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If penalties reduce a target number to 0 or less, any attempt to use it automatically results in failure. The character must find another way to achieve his aim.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.5.1 Stretches\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you propose an action using an ability that seems completely inappropriate, the GM rules it impossible. If you went ahead and tried it anyway, you\u8217'd automatically fail\u8212-but you won\u8217't, because that would be silly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In some cases, though, your proposed match-up of action and ability is only somewhat implausible. A successful attempt with it wouldn\u8217't completely break the illusion of fictional reality\u8212-just stretch it a bit.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Using a somewhat implausible ability is known as a stretch. If the GM deems an attempt to be a stretch, the PC suffers a \u8211-6 penalty to their target number.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The definition of stretch is elastic, depending on genre.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 GMs should not impose stretch penalties on action descriptions that add flavor and variety to a scene, but do not fundamentally change what the character can do with his ability. These make the scene more fun but don\u8217't really gain any advantage.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.5.2 Situational Modifiers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 GMs may also impose modifiers when, given the description of the current situation, believability demands that a character should face a notable advantage or disadvantage. Assess modifiers of +6, +3, \u8211-3, or \u8211-6. Modi ers of less than 3 don\u8217't exert enough statistical effect to be worth the bother. Those higher than 6 give the situational modi er a disproportionate role in determining results.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 During an extended contest, they should typically last for a single exchange, and reflect clever or foolish choices by the character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.5.3 Engaging Multiple Opponents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If more than one opponent engages a PC (or NPC), they take part in a number of contests equal to the number of opponents. For each extra contest they are forced to participate in during a given round, they suffer a cumulative -3 penalty.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A GM should resolve all engagements against a single PC/NPC at once, adjusting the order of action as necessary. A player can choose the order in which their PC engages their respective opponents. It\u8217's usually smartest to engage them in order of relative toughness, from highest to lowest rating.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.6 Optional: Combined Abilities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On certain occasions the GM may rule that a character can only hope to achieve his goal by using two disparate abilities. When this occurs, average the two ability ratings, then apply any modifiers, to arrive at the target number.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Combining abilities, rather than using the best one and augmenting it with other, is always a disadvantage to the character. The GM should only require combined ability use when story logic absolutely demands that the character face a lower chance of success, because he has to do two things at once.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.7 Mobs, Gangs, and Hordes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes the PCs will face large numbers of individually inconsequential opponents. The GM can roll for each of them separately, taking note of the multiple opponent penalties they incur against their enemies. More simply, the GM can treat many as one. Divide the number of minor opponents by the number of contesting PCs. Treat each of these sections of the crowd as a single character with one ability rating. They don\u8217't impose a multiple opponent penalty; instead, their numbers are factored into the ability rating the GM assigns to them. When the mob loses an exchange, the GM describes individuals within it as being hurt or falling away. When it wins, describe them overwhelming the PC, or swelling in numbers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.8 Mass Effort\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Clashes of massive forces resolve like any other contest, simple or extended, solo or group. These include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Military engagements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Corporate struggles for market share \u8226? Building competitions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Efforts to spread a faith or ideology \u8226? Dance competitions\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the PCs are not participating in the contest and have no stake in its outcome, don\u8217't bother to run a contest. Just choose an outcome for dramatic purposes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Otherwise, start by determining the PC or PCs\u8217' degree of influence over the outcome. They are either:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Determining factors: The success of the effort depends mostly on their choices and successes. For example, they might be military leaders facing a force of roughly equal potency. As all else is equal, the better general will win the day. In this instance, the PC or PCs contest a relevant leadership ability against those of opposing leaders.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Contributors: One of the forces enjoys a clear advantage over the others, but the PC\u8217's efforts may tip the balance in favor of a chosen side. A player or players contest with a rating representing the strength of the force, but can augment its rating with a PC ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Acted Upon: The PCs have little in uence over the outcome, but are stuck in the middle of the conflict and must struggle to prosper within it. The GM predetermines the outcome of the overall competition on dramatic grounds. Each PC contests against a rating determined by the GM. Contest winners gain lingering benefits, while losers suffer states of adversity\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.10 Pyrrhic Victories\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In a Pyrrhic victory, players boost their chances of success in a contest by accepting negative consequences at its end, even if they win the prize around which it is framed. The PCs each gain a mastery in the abilities they\u8217're using to prosecute the contest. At the contest\u8217's end, they suffer the following states of adversity, as per the Pyrrhic Victory Table.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As with any proposed action, the players must convincingly describe the potentially suicidal risks the PCs are taking to achieve their objective. They must also show how these risks can bring them the awful victory they seek.\par}
