{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.2.4 Optional Consequences and Benefits\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Depending on which approach seems to grow from the story, Consequences of Defeat or Benefits of Victory from Group Simple Contests may be assigned to the entire group, or to individual members who performed either especially well, or especially poorly. Default to rewarding or penalizing everyone. Resort to individualized repercussions or benefits only when a group reward defies dramatic credibility, or when competition within the group is a pivotal dramatic issue.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.2.5 Optional: Boosting Results\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Because they average together the results of multiple participants, group simple contests tend to flatten outcomes, making victories more likely to be marginal or minor than major or complete.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To overcome this flattening effect, players can, at the beginning of a group simple contest, to spend one or more Hero Points to purchase a boost. A boost assures a clearer victory, should they prevail.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The cost varies by the number of heroes participating:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 Hero Point for 1-3 heroes;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 2 Hero Points for 4-6 heroes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 3 Hero Points for 7-9 heroes.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab and so on\u8230?\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Groups may spend twice as many Hero Points as required to gain a double boost. The points may be spent by any combination of players. They remain spent no matter how the contest resolves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On a tie or a victory, the boost increases the collective victory level by one step. A double boost increases it by two steps.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 6. Hero Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Hero points are a resource that players must carefully allocate. They allow you to heighten your victories and dull your defeats. They are the price you pay to improve your abilities over time. They are also used in a few unusual adjudications\u8212-resolving tied results between PCs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.1 Gaining Hero Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You get 3 hero points at the beginning of every session. During the session, all Hero Points must be spent, either on improving contest results or character improvement. At the end of the session, unspent points are lost.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.2 Improving Your Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may improve any ability by 1 point per session, at a cost of 1 hero point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It costs 1 Hero Point to raise a single breakout ability under the keyword, or 2 points to raise the entire keyword or runic affinity by a point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can add a new ability by spending 1 point; it begins with a rating of 13.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can add a new breakout ability by spending 1 point; it begins with a rating of +1 to the keyword it modifies\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.3 Catch-Ups\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A package deal, called a catch-up, applies whenever you acquire a new mastery, up to three abilities or keywords of your choice also increase by 3 points apiece. Only abilities or keywords with values 5 or more points behind your newly adjusted rating in the raised ability qualify for a catch-up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can\u8217't raise abilities under a keyword, nor gain a catch-up when the effective value of a subability reaches a mastery (since it\u8217's the keyword, not the abilities under it, which has a rating).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.4 Directed Improvements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On occasion a Narrator may increase one of your abilities, by 1 to 3 points, or give you a new ability, usually rated at 13. These are called directed improvements.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Ability increases are usually rewards for overcoming particularly important or dramatic obstacles. They happen immediately, rather than at session\u8217's end.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 7. Relationships\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Abilities may represent the relationship of the PC to supporting characters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.1 Supporting Characters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many relationships connect the PC to supporting characters controlled by the Game Master.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When the PC tries to use one of these relationships to solve a problem, they contest with their relationship ability. The PC can\u8217't simply go to the supporting character they have a relationship with, stick them with the problem, and expect to see it solved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the PC succeeds, the supporting character helps them solve the problem. If they fail, they don\u8217't. As with any ability, the player must still specify how the contact goes about overcoming the obstacle. Calls on relationships are almost always simple contests.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In crucial situations, it may seem dramatically inappropriate for a PC to solve a problem indirectly, by working through others. The Game Master can expose the supporting character to serious risk. If the character dies or otherwise suffers a change of status that renders him useless to the PC, the PC permanently loses the relationship ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before putting supporting characters at serious risk, Game Masters should make sure the players understand the magnitude of the possible consequences.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When supporting characters undertake significant risk, the supporting character may suffer a consequence of defeat commensurate with the level of the defeat in the contest. Or it may simply be the PC\u8217's relationship with that is damaged or destroyed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.2 Allies\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An ally is a character of roughly the same level of accomplishment as the PC, often in the same or a similar line of work. For every favor a PC asks of them, they\u8217'll ask one of them. These reciprocal favors will be roughly equivalent in terms of risk, time commitment, difficulty, and inconvenience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.3 Patrons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Patrons enjoy greater access to resources than the PC, either through personal ownership (as in a Merchant Prince) or authority (as in the governnor of a province). They may lend the PC advice or provide them with resources but are too busy and important to personally perform tasks for them. They may hire the PC to do jobs, or issue orders within a command structure to which they both belong.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When a PC rolls their Patron relationship, the Game Master adjusts the difficulty depending on what the PC has done for them lately.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.4 Contacts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A contact is a specialist in an occupation, skill, or area of expertise. Contacts provide information and perform minor favors, but will expect information or small favors from the PC in return.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can describe a contact as being a particular individual, or as a group of similar individuals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.4.1 Occupational Contacts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any occupational keyword can be treated as a source of contacts. However, using an occupational keyword as a source of contacts will always be a stretch. To more reliably draw on particular contacts associated with a profession, a PC should take an explicit ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.5 Followers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A follower is a secondary character that travels with the PC and contributes on a regular basis to their success.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two types of followers: sidekicks and retainers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Followers need not be people, or even sentient beings: you can write up a spirit guardian, trusty robot, or companion animal as a follower.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.5.1 Sidekick\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sidekick is a secondary character under the player\u8217's control. Most of the time they stays at the PC\u8217's side to render assistance, but they can also go off and perform errands or missions on their own.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The PC should give their sidekick a name. They should, when asked, explain how the sidekick came to be the PC\u8217's follower, and why they continues in that role.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sidekicks start with three abilities, one rated at 17 and the others at 13. Any of these abilities may be a keyword. At least one of them should indicate a personality trait.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the sidekick is nonhuman or a member of an unusual culture, one of its three starting abilities must be its species or culture keyword.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once the PC has determined the sidekick\u8217's base abilities, they allocate 15 additional points between three of them, spending no more than 10 on any one ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These abilities, like those of the PC, can be improved through the expenditure of Hero Points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A player may use any of the sidekick\u8217's abilities as they would their PC\u8217's. The companion can go off and do things without the PC.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.5.2 Replacing Lost Sidekicks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As a consequence of defeats in which they participated, sidekicks can be killed or leave the PC\u8217's service permanently.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Defeat in physical contests can lead to literal death. Metaphorical deaths from non-violent contests indicate a break with the PC. The sidekick may angrily withdraw from service, but is more likely to sorrowfully retire. A PC may be able to bring a sidekick back from metaphorical death by overcoming story obstacles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a player loses a sidekick, they may create a new one without needing to spend a Hero Point. They must explain how the new sidekick has come to be their new follower.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PCs with retainers may find it convenient to promote them to sidekick status, giving them names and personalities, with a sudden boost in abilities and ratings to match.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.5.3 Retainers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A retainer is a more or less anonymous servant or helper. The PC may specify a single retainer, or, where appropriate to the character concept, an entire staff of them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Like any other ability, a retainer ability allows the player to overcome relevant obstacles by engaging in a contest. To model the contribution of retainers to the PC, where the PC is the primary actor, the player can use them to augment their ability. The GM can rule that consequences of defeat apply to retainers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Retainers generally regard the PC with all the affection and loyalty due to an employer or master. If the PC treats them more poorly than is expected for their culture, the GM should increase the difficulty level of attempts to make use of their talents.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the PC loses retainers for any reason, they can replace them simply by providing a convincing explanation of how you go about it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.6 Relationships as Flaws\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Certain relationships with supporting characters act as flaws. They impose obligations on the PC, prompting the GM to present the PC with obstacles they have no choice but to overcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.6.1 Dependents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A dependent is a person, usually a family member or loved one, who requires the PCs aid and protection. The GM should periodically create storylines in which the dependent is endangered.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Rather than taking a dependent as a flaw, the player may find it more fruitful to specify the nature of the PC\u8217's relationship as an ability, such as Love for Wife or Love for Son.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.6.2 Adversaries\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An adversary is a rival, enemy or other individual who can be relied upon to periodically disrupt the PC\u8217's plans.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 THe adversary\u8217's goals are probably the opposite of the PC\u8217's, although he could be a bitter rival within the same community, organization, or movement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To treat an adversary as an ability, rather than a flaw, describe the PC\u8217's emotional response to them. Examples: Hates Leonard Crisp, Fears the Electronaut, Sworn Vengeance Against Heimdall. That way, you still inspire the Narrator to add the plot elements you desire, but can use your antipathy toward the enemy to augment your target numbers against them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 8. Optional: Extended Contests\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 8.1 Extended Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 8.1.1 Procedure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Frame the contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Figure the PC\u8217's target number (TN) using the ability rating and any modifiers. The PCs TN is the rating of their ability, plus or minus modifiers the GM may give the PC.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab The GM determines the resistance. The GM opposes the PC with a resistance\u8212-the harder the task or tougher the opponent, the higher the resistance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Carry out one or more rounds, repeating as necessary.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab An extended contest unfolds as a series of simple contests. At the end of each simple contest, the winning character (or resistance) scores a number of resolution points (RPs) to his tally, which varies between 1 and 5, depending on the result. Tied results leave the score unchanged.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab The number of resolution points the winner garners at the end of each exchange depends on the degree of victory they scored. They get 1 point for a marginal victory, 2 for a minor victory, 3 for a major victory, and 5 for a complete victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab The first of the contesting characters to accumulate a total of 5 points wins; their opponent is knocked out of the contest and loses the prize.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Determine Degee of Succes based on Rising Action of Climax (below).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Determine Benefits of Victory or Consequences of Defeat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 7.\tx360\tab Describe the result based on the agreed prize.\sa180\par}
